Observation Details: Continuing/known location; same flock as yesterday, but in location slightly E of Family Dollar/warehouse lot. Crows, gulls, and starlings were coming to seed and bread that was left on Old Broadway street (apparently by the lone residence there) immediately adjacent to the railroad tracks. Max FICR count at one time was 16 feeding on the ground with 2-3 AMCR mixed in. Another 50 crow sp were along the tracks in the vicinity, the majority of which were presumably AMCR. Less calling (nasal “ahhs”) today in colder/windier conditions, but proportionately shorter bills and legs, and smaller size/more compact blackbird-like shape were distinctive in direct comparison to the few mixing AMCR. The flock eventually dispersed off to the NW when a train came through and did not return over the next 15 minutes. Photos and recordings (mix of FICR and AMCR calls).

Observation Details: I was heading back from the east side of Dead Pond Trail, and starting to load my gear into the car at Thompson's Circle, when I heard a short, nasal, pure-toned, single 'caa'.  It immediately sounded like a Fish Crow to me, with the higher pitch drawing my attention the most to it, so I stopped loading my gear to listen again.  Around 20 seconds later it gave the same distinctive call note again.  I pulled out my recorder and took some quick photos of the bird, but the bird flew off within 30 seconds, not vocalizing again.  Unfortunately, good profile views of it in flight were obstructed by trees in Thompson Circle.  The bird flew towards the Beach 11 area not looking like it was going to land there.  Lots of experience with Fish Crows in Cape May last March and some in other areas in the northeast and Texas.  A species continuing to increase its range.  Like other stationary counts from Gary, IN to Mexico, NY, a bird likely to be recorded every 1-3 years in spring flying along the ridge, with multiples in a spring likely to come in the near future.  Very curious as to how many of these will be in the interior of the park in the next decade though.

Giving nasal 'awwr' or 'awwp' calls and occasional short nasal 'uh' calls. There appeared to be a single bird circling the area. In response to playback it performed a 'V' wing display with feet dangling. This is a short glide with some quick wing beats interspersed. Longer and narrower tail than nearby (calling) American Crows. Photos show p9>p6 and only four longest fingers as opposed to five on American. This bird also appeared smaller and shorter billed with smaller feet than American Crows. The bird did not show obvious wing molt; however many of the American Crows were in wing molt, replacing inner primaries especially. The Fish Crow did appear to be renewing outer rectrices.  Single birds to one or two pairs have summered at this location for a few years now. I hadn't made but passing attempts to find the birds before today.

Photos linked below were all taken at this site during this visit.    The bird was very tame, allowing close approach and feeding on the expected urban detritus, including a road-killed small bird, a discarded roll, and various other quasi-food items. Several items were taken to a puddle where they were immersed in water before being eaten.    The bird vocalized a lot initially, always giving single syllabled "ahh" calls with a nasal quality. We left ten minutes later when the bird flew south and we pursued it.                        Andy posted a description to the ID-Frontiers listserv, and responses so far have all supported this identification, including those from Brian Sullivan, David Sibley, Kevin McGowan, and Michael OBrien.

Why does the Trowbridge gate trash can often have garbage spilled onto the ground?  Note added Saturday evening, May 7:  Most remarkably, after having studied Common Ravens 'up close and personal' at West Rock over the past twenty years (including a dumpster diving raven adult male at the nearby Katz's Restaurant), in now reviewing these photos I began to doubt this identification of two corvids as being Fish Crows. The heavy beak, spatulate tail, and bristle feathers on the beak all now suggest Common Raven.  Yet, prior to my photographing the birds at East Rock, I heard two Fish Crows calling in the immediate vicinity. The photos are of two different corvids raiding the Trowbridge Drive gate trash can. Their size, as apparent to me at the time, was not consistent with raven but was with Fish Crow. While the photos also suggest smaller corvids than ravens, some of the features want to shout out raven! The closed mind can play curious tricks. Time to check out museum specimens of Fish Crow to confirm that my brain settled on the correct identification.

Observation Details: Very conservative count.  Audio did not come out well due to vehicle noises.  Distinctive "uh-uh" call heard from several birds.  Majority of flock smaller than AMCR, despite that not being sufficient alone to separate species.  I saw many more birds, presumably more FICR, sitting under the eaves of the Olive Garden and flying around the plaza areas.  I think it is safe to say that there are 75 FICR at the very least, and probably many more than that.  A more complete survey would be helpful to get a sense of the growing wintering population at the Chapel Hill area, and more importantly where these birds are nesting during the spring/summer months.

Max FICR count at one time was 16 feeding on the ground with 2-3 AMCR mixed in. Another 50 crow sp were along the tracks in the vicinity, the majority of which were presumably AMCR. Less calling (nasal “ahhs”) today in colder/windier conditions, but proportionately shorter bills and legs, and smaller size/more compact blackbird-like shape were distinctive in direct comparison to the few mixing AMCR. The flock eventually dispersed off to the NW when a train came through and did not return over the next 15 minutes. Photos and recordings (mix of FICR and AMCR calls).

Observation Details: I counted 110 crows in this flock and I believe that most of them were Fish Crows. Small-billed. Several nasal FICR calls heard, much quieter than the one or two AMCR calling occasionally. Foraging and resting and preening. Allowed me to approach closely and make careful comparisons. Photos sent to crow expert, Kevin McGowan, who confirmed that almost all of the birds in my photos were FICRs. He based this on the short legs, small feet, and the distinctive to him, face and bill profile, as well as the wing formula on flying birds. Although I did not actually see an American Crow in the field, I heard at least one, and Kevin thinks that two birds in my photos are American Crows. So, I assume that I missed a few and am reducing the number of FICRs to a conservative 90.

Observation Details: Why does the Trowbridge gate trash can often have garbage spilled onto the ground?  Note added Saturday evening, May 7:  Most remarkably, after having studied Common Ravens 'up close and personal' at West Rock over the past twenty years (including a dumpster diving raven adult male at the nearby Katz's Restaurant), in now reviewing these photos I began to doubt this identification of two corvids as being Fish Crows. The heavy beak, spatulate tail, and bristle feathers on the beak all now suggest Common Raven.  Yet, prior to my photographing the birds at East Rock, I heard two Fish Crows calling in the immediate vicinity. The photos are of two different corvids raiding the Trowbridge Drive gate trash can. Their size, as apparent to me at the time, was not consistent with raven but was with Fish Crow. While the photos also suggest smaller corvids than ravens, some of the features want to shout out raven! The closed mind can play curious tricks. Time to check out museum specimens of Fish Crow to confirm that my brain settled on the correct identification.

Extremely rare anywhere in Michigan outside of Berrien county. First Allegan Co. record, if accepted. Full documentation to be submitted to MBRC.   Circumstances: At 10:16 AM I began to hear 3-4 single note vocalizations to my east, which I immediately recognized as Fish Crow based on having heard them hundreds to thousands of times throughout the southeast (especially in Florida), but also SC, AR, MO, NJ, OH, and in Berrien Co. MI. I am fully aware of the similarity of juvenile American Crow vocalizations, and every call I heard was instantly recognizable as the classic single note of Fish Crow. The note was "tinny," hollow, and higher pitched than that of American, without any of the harsh or grating tones, and was not variable or suggestive of whisper song, as one often hears from juvenile Americans. By the end of the encounter, which lasted just over a minute, I heard single vocalizations over ten times, though I didn't specifically count them, and the vocalization was consistent and classic for Fish Crow. I didn't hear any double notes.   Upon turning and looking in the direction of the first calls, there was a tight, cohesive flock of 5 crows wheeling roughly NW, and coming from the SE, and the calls were clearly coming from this flock. They were all the same size, with no individuals appearing larger or smaller than the others, and no American Crow vocalizations were heard at any time during the observation. American Crows, which were omnipresent throughout the rest of the day, nearly always vocalize. This is not proof that none of the 5 weren't Americans. But my suspicion is that all five were Fish Crows. However, I am only claiming one individual, on the basis of the fact that I never clearly heard two Fish Crows vocalizing at the same time, and that the birds identifiable as Fish Crows in my photos, and not provably different individuals. Conservatively, therefore, I am only claiming one Fish Crow.  As the 5 individual crows came closer, they passed directly overhead, within probably 50-100', when I was able to get excellent photos of one of the birds at close range (the best three photos are the same individual), and farther photos of what may or may not be another individual than the first one. In each of these photos it is very straightforward to see that p9 is longer than p5, which eliminates American Crow, in which p9 is shorter than p5.  Immediately after they passed overhead, and continued northwesterly toward the lakeshore, both Tomas Pedreros and I (the only two birders present) attempted to get sound recordings, Tomas using the video feature on an iPhone and myself using Voice Recorder on an iPhone. Frustratingly, although we heard several more calls, they do not appear to be audible in either recording. The birds continued northwest until out of site, and were not heard or seen again despite us staying on site until 1:30PM.

Observation Details: Second county record, first photo record. Found with a flock of American Crows harassing a Red-tailed Hawk. When they were all perched on the wire single file it stuck out like a sore thumb with how much smaller it was than the Americans. The legs appeared a bit shorter as well, and I was able to get a photo of it in flight with an American that actually shows the shorter legs. When it flew it had a bit of a noticeable difference in flight style, but I wasn’t really thinking at the time to take much note of that and focused more on securing photos of the wing shape and primaries. I was able to get photos that showed the longer central primaries which gave the bird more of a pointed wing shape than the more rounded shape of the Americans. Though not diagnostic on its own, I did notice that it seemed a little more glossy and colorful when the sun hit it than the other Americans around it. I tried to stay on it the flock flew off but they soon disappeared heading south along Kenny Road.

Locality: Sanibel Island (please consider using a more precise location)

Observation Details: Giving nasal 'awwr' or 'awwp' calls and occasional short nasal 'uh' calls. There appeared to be a single bird circling the area. In response to playback it performed a 'V' wing display with feet dangling. This is a short glide with some quick wing beats interspersed. Longer and narrower tail than nearby (calling) American Crows. Photos show p9>p6 and only four longest fingers as opposed to five on American. This bird also appeared smaller and shorter billed with smaller feet than American Crows. The bird did not show obvious wing molt; however many of the American Crows were in wing molt, replacing inner primaries especially. The Fish Crow did appear to be renewing outer rectrices.  Single birds to one or two pairs have summered at this location for a few years now. I hadn't made but passing attempts to find the birds before today.

Exact count. This pure flock of 14 Fish Crows was originally on the west side of the Eco park, I followed them through the neighbourhoods to Sunset Beach, where I photographed a number of the birds. Certainly the same flock I saw with Todd Hagedorn on April 20 on the Port Weller east pier. Distinctive vocalizations, calling posture, flapping style, relatively swept-back wings in flight, etc. I think this is a record high count for Ontario.

**Extraordinarily high. 1x1 tally of birds flying south along the river.   Fairly early in my walk there were 2 large streams of exclusively Fish Crows heading south (141 & 146 separated by ~20 minutes). These birds were mostly coming in groups of 5-15, and at least 75% of these birds early were calling, making for easy IDs. With 4 stragglers my count sat at 291 (already good for a personal high count, besting the Great Hill mid-summer roost in Weymouth).   However, right as I was about to leave, I heard a much larger flock flying overhead, and raced back to get a better vantage to count them. This pulse of 401 passed in a few minutes, and I strained to keep up my 1x1 tally and not resort to estimating or counting by 5s or 10s. There were then more birds streaming for the next half hour, but at a slower rate that allowed for easier counting (and separating out the handful of American Crows that were coming by at this time).   This count of 1177 obliterated the previous Norfolk County high count set just this month (480 on 11/1/23 at Noon Hill), and is a new high count for the South Shore. There is one Barnstable County count of 1200 in February of birds coming in to Falmouth from Marta's Vineyard (https://ebird.org/checklist/S65273943); otherwise this count is the highest count for the state away from the Lawrence Crow Roost. Even there the high count on eBird for Fish Crows is "only" 1500 (not including a 10,000 count that seems to be a mistake), though I'd imagine a great deal of estimating between the species counts is required there. This is also the new high count for the state during the fall (or indeed any month but January/February). This is all a long way of saying this was an incredible showing and I'm glad I started counting 1x1 right away!  Showing my work: First two streams earlier in the walk: 141, 146, 4  2:35pm: 401, 36, 35, 164, 66, 26, 9, 16, 34, 42  3:10pm: 43, 4, 3, 1

Documentation to be sent to MBRC, in response to positive feedback from Kevin McGowan, Adam Byrne, and others that nothing this bird is doing is wrong for pure FICR, and there is no evidence of hybridization. In downtown Saugtauck - first reported yesterday at this on Water St between Mary and Lucy yesterday by Martin Blagdurn, including a recording which sounded exactly like FICR, hence my attempt to chase it. I found this individual at the same location, however when I found it it was alternating between what I interpret as normal Fish Crow vocalizations (the single note, never the double note, as all Fish Crows in Michigan do) and American Crow calls. From the beginning of the observation the bird appeared consistently smaller-bodied than American Crow, with a noticeably dainty and decurved bill. In all of my photos of it in flight, P9 is clearly longer than p5, given as diagnostic of Fish Crow in the literature. Neither Pyle or the Handbook of Avian Hybrids lists any published or suspected hybridization events involving Fish Crow. However, one wonders if a lone Fish Crow vagrant which reached this area might hybridize with Americans when that is the only available option. Active flight feather molt at p7 shows that this is an after hatching year individual, and molt timing favors Fish Crow, which molts on average at this latitude a month later than American Crow (which finishes in Sept while FICR finishes in October).   Recordings:   https://soundcloud.com/user9140545/fish-type-crow-saugatuck-mi-9112022?si=f75482fc34f443f9bdc0cf670b96b774&utm_source=clipboard&utm_medium=text&utm_campaign=social_sharing   https://soundcloud.com/user9140545/fish-type-crow-saugatuck-mi-9112022-b?si=f75482fc34f443f9bdc0cf670b96b774&utm_source=clipboard&utm_medium=text&utm_campaign=social_sharing

Observation Details: Why does the Trowbridge gate trash can often have garbage spilled onto the ground?  Note added Saturday evening, May 7:  Most remarkably, after having studied Common Ravens 'up close and personal' at West Rock over the past twenty years (including a dumpster diving raven adult male at the nearby Katz's Restaurant), in now reviewing these photos I began to doubt this identification of two corvids as being Fish Crows. The heavy beak, spatulate tail, and bristle feathers on the beak all now suggest Common Raven.  Yet, prior to my photographing the birds at East Rock, I heard two Fish Crows calling in the immediate vicinity. The photos are of two different corvids raiding the Trowbridge Drive gate trash can. Their size, as apparent to me at the time, was not consistent with raven but was with Fish Crow. While the photos also suggest smaller corvids than ravens, some of the features want to shout out raven! The closed mind can play curious tricks. Time to check out museum specimens of Fish Crow to confirm that my brain settled on the correct identification.

Observation Details: Apparently mated male/female pair and third individual that stays close and is tolerated for the most part, but often chased away by what appears to be the female. Their “Birds of the World” account states this is apparently a frequent occurrence during the nesting stage. All three vocalized together for great identification opportunity. Male often goes to rest on the ledge of the large window over the Giant Eagle entrance, calling while facing the window in what seems like an attempt to amplify his voice over all of the background noise. Lots of single note, high-pitched and nasal “caw” calls with quite a bit of triple “caw-caw-caw” calls mixed in but not very many double “UH-uh” calls heard. Observed carrying sticks twice. Once they flew to the south with a stick towards the neighborhood around Henderson Road, the other time the female appeared to go east along Bethel with a stick and then return without it. Attempted to locate nest and found four good candidates but not sure if they are current or old as no birds were seen actively visiting them.

I was heading back from the east side of Dead Pond Trail, and starting to load my gear into the car at Thompson's Circle, when I heard a short, nasal, pure-toned, single 'caa'.  It immediately sounded like a Fish Crow to me, with the higher pitch drawing my attention the most to it, so I stopped loading my gear to listen again.  Around 20 seconds later it gave the same distinctive call note again.  I pulled out my recorder and took some quick photos of the bird, but the bird flew off within 30 seconds, not vocalizing again.  Unfortunately, good profile views of it in flight were obstructed by trees in Thompson Circle.  The bird flew towards the Beach 11 area not looking like it was going to land there.  Lots of experience with Fish Crows in Cape May last March and some in other areas in the northeast and Texas.  A species continuing to increase its range.  Like other stationary counts from Gary, IN to Mexico, NY, a bird likely to be recorded every 1-3 years in spring flying along the ridge, with multiples in a spring likely to come in the near future.  Very curious as to how many of these will be in the interior of the park in the next decade though.

The  chick that I have called “Adam” has fledged and flies from tree to tree begging for parental attention! Mostly in the NW region of Adamson Estate where there are two scruffy pines and some tall White Oaks.    Parents regularly come over to attend to “Adam” by regurgitating food into his beak or onto branches and the chick feeds off the branch.   A great deal of interaction between parents and chicks, including branch picking and branch breaking...as if to build another nest or roost..   A fair amount of vocalization by all the family members. Adam the chick , at one point, gave a weirdly shrieking call while diving...it seems that it discovered GRAVITY and that wings must be used to offset GRAVITY!!!.   Parents still very territorial, but did not visit the nest at all. They would just fly by it.   No sign of the second chick “Eve”. Since Friday the 13th ( the last time both chicks were observed being fed at their nest) there has only been one chick observed. Who knows where the other fledged chick has ended up. It definitely is not in or near the nest.     Too many videos and pics taken!!!

Observation Details: Bird was found by Ken Edwards in the morning near Lighthouse. I arrived at 3:30 pm and found the bird within 75 m of the place found. Flew down from the north and perched on the last few trees. We walked right up to it, uh-uhed at it and it began calling. It stayed for around 20 minutes. It allowed extremely close approach and excellent point-blank looks, and fed on a few dogwood berries before taking off. Fish Crow features seen include - still in molt, including a couple of primaries - American Crow finishes molt earlier, very purplish sheen to new feathers, hooked bill, pointy-winged appearance and flappier flight, voice and calling posture. They aren't always this cooperative!

Merlin sound app registered exclusively as Fish Crow. Short upper legs, thin bodies, long thin P9 feathers much longer than P5 feathers giving wings swept back and pointed appearance in flight (conforming with Fish Crow pics I took in Florida). Observed birds for ten minutes until the Blue Jay mob forced flight SW over the Sweetbriar Golf Course. I am not 100% positive on this ID but there were no American Crows nearby that I detected. Observation Details: This presumed mated pair are occurring regularly here recently. Two relatively small crows, hopping around in the grass along the point in very typical FICR fashion. I was still unsure initially, so played a two note FICR call, which one of the birds repeated. Largely silent otherwise, except for more "caw" like calls at one point, but thinner and more nasal than AMCR.  Extended close looks gave me time to study them. Bill slightly shorter than AMCR. Twice they carried off chunks of food to the trees around the corner from the cormorant roost point, which I think is solid evidence of a nest back there.   Upon departing with food the second time, two AMCR came in to harass them, chasing close and giving nice comparison looks of the two species in flight.

Observation Details: Edit: bird was treated by Wild Bird Fund and released back into Shore Road Park on 7/28! Big shout out to WBF and Jimmy Johnson from Narrows Botanical Garden for helping this bird to have a future. Video of the bird’s release, and original notes   https://m.facebook.com/groups/54673582472/posts/10159221325532473   Severely injured or seriously ill bird, carefully and perhaps somewhat foolishly extracted on foot from the shoulder of the Belt Parkway in midday traffic. Brought to Narrows Botanical Garden on 70th street, which works closely with Wild Bird Fund, where it was immediately given private quarters. Had enough energy for a few big flaps, but was overall listless and did not resist being picked up at all. Looked nearly dead in the car, but immediately perched on a log when placed in an enclosure. Hopeful, but not optimistic. Silent, but appreciably small, slender, and long-tailed in the hand. Not in my possession and certainly not in the hand any longer than necessary. Possibly one of the birds that nest across the street in Shore Road Park, but could be a member of the Hoffman Island night roost as well.

Observation Details: Why does the Trowbridge gate trash can often have garbage spilled onto the ground?  Note added Saturday evening, May 7:  Most remarkably, after having studied Common Ravens 'up close and personal' at West Rock over the past twenty years (including a dumpster diving raven adult male at the nearby Katz's Restaurant), in now reviewing these photos I began to doubt this identification of two corvids as being Fish Crows. The heavy beak, spatulate tail, and bristle feathers on the beak all now suggest Common Raven.  Yet, prior to my photographing the birds at East Rock, I heard two Fish Crows calling in the immediate vicinity. The photos are of two different corvids raiding the Trowbridge Drive gate trash can. Their size, as apparent to me at the time, was not consistent with raven but was with Fish Crow. While the photos also suggest smaller corvids than ravens, some of the features want to shout out raven! The closed mind can play curious tricks. Time to check out museum specimens of Fish Crow to confirm that my brain settled on the correct identification.

Observation Details: Continuing/known location; same flock as yesterday, but in location slightly E of Family Dollar/warehouse lot. Crows, gulls, and starlings were coming to seed and bread that was left on Old Broadway street (apparently by the lone residence there) immediately adjacent to the railroad tracks. Max FICR count at one time was 16 feeding on the ground with 2-3 AMCR mixed in. Another 50 crow sp were along the tracks in the vicinity, the majority of which were presumably AMCR. The flock eventually dispersed off to the NW when a train came through and did not return over the next 15 minutes. Photos and recordings (mix of FICR and AMCR calls).

Locality: Fish Crow stakeout at Sawmill and Bethel intersection
Observation Details: Major Boom on Fish Crow sightings in Franklin County over the course of 2 weeks.  This time Mael Glon had accurately identified and reported the presence of pair calling at the CVS on the corner of Bethel and Sawmill.  Mollie Langdon had corroborated his report with a legitimate recording on the same day.  Andy Sewell recorded a video the next morning and shared it within our county birding group-which kindled the necessary fire within to pursue.  Fortunately the birds were still present a few hours later the same morning and I was able to get a few recordings and some pictures to confirm.

Présence connue depuis plusieurs jours. Deux individus vu et entendu à plusieurs reprises. Sur la première photo, la Corneille de rivage semble avoir les pattes plus courte que la Corneille d'Amérique. Faits intéressants, sur trois photos, on peut voir la Corneille de rivage éplucher l'écorce de fines branches pour servir à la construction du nid. Cette corneille a aussi émis son cri distinctif pendant son travail. Les deux individus ont aussi voyagés dans un grand Pin où l'on ne peut voir le nid caché par les branches et très haut.

Observation Details: Two picked out by voice when a small crowd rose up from the Boston Market lot. More hanging around the McDonald’s, likely an undercount but there was a lot of crow action making a count difficult. They appeared to know quite well what was happening around the restaurants. We had heard that Fish Crows have shorter legs than American but had never had the opportunity to compare - they did seem shorter especially when they congregated on the asphalt. The birds were a touch smaller in appearance than the American Crows. Four at least in the median trees N of McD from which I eventually captured a few calls with moderate traffic. Not our favorite habitat, probably not theirs either, but they do seem to be making a living.

Media notes: Fish Crow (left) in pursuit by American Crow (right) demonstrating difference in primaries - p5 much longer in AMCR, giving rounded appearance and 5 prominent primary "fingers"
Observation Details: This presumed mated pair are occurring regularly here recently. Two relatively small crows, hopping around in the grass along the point in very typical FICR fashion. I was still unsure initially, so played a two note FICR call, which one of the birds repeated. Largely silent otherwise, except for more "caw" like calls at one point, but thinner and more nasal than AMCR.  Extended close looks gave me time to study them. Bill slightly shorter than AMCR. Twice they carried off chunks of food to the trees around the corner from the cormorant roost point, which I think is solid evidence of a nest back there.   Upon departing with food the second time, two AMCR came in to harass them, chasing close and giving nice comparison looks of the two species in flight.

Observation Details: Rough estimate.  More flying in as I left.

I came outside to wait for my brother to get home so I could tell him about the FICR I got earlier. As soon as I stepped outside I heard the nasal "eh-uh" call again. I ran into the open, and four crows were flying, but one was higher and not closely associating with the others. I watched it soar and go a bit away, and then slowly it returned calling and landed (out of site) in some neighbouring trees. I ran inside and got my camera and binoculars and by that time my brother was home. Not long after, the three American crows started attacking the FICR, which gave for a good comparison and very distinctive difference in behavior.  A couple of things that fit FICR better were: "Longer tail -- more tapered wings -- slightly smaller -- distinct nasal "eh-uh" and "cah" calls."
Sounded like Fish Crows.

Locality: Plaza at Chapel Hill Shopping Center
Observation Details: Very conservative count.  Audio did not come out well due to vehicle noises.  Distinctive "uh-uh" call heard from several birds.  Majority of flock smaller than AMCR, despite that not being sufficient alone to separate species.  I saw many more birds, presumably more FICR, sitting under the eaves of the Olive Garden and flying around the plaza areas.  I think it is safe to say that there are 75 FICR at the very least, and probably many more than that.  A more complete survey would be helpful to get a sense of the growing wintering population at the Chapel Hill area, and more importantly where these birds are nesting during the spring/summer months.

While photographing the Kingfisher, through the corner of my eye I observed a crow land near the bottom of the pile of mounded earth. I paid little attention to it until I finished taking pictures of the Kingfisher. Now studying the crow I first noticed it's blotchy body colour and several white downy like feathers on the crown. As the bird moved around the earth looking for food it appeared to me to be smaller and the legs gave me the impression of being longer. As well the tail appeared to be more rounded. Josh Vandermeulen who lives nearby has reported hearing and observing Fish Crows near his residence. While nesting nearby was a possibility I am not sure if this individual was a hatch year bird. Up to this point the crow I was viewing had remained totally silent but on lift-off gave several short nasal arruk, arruk, arruk arruk calls. Based on all of the above....I am certain this bird was a Fish Crow.

We watched the remnants of the Calidrid (small) sandpiper migration at Bronte in mid-day. As we were back at our car we noticed two crows flying purposefully in from the east. They circled the harbour restaurant and flew up to the former Cliff Swallow nests under the eaves of this building. Running back to the spot we were within hearing and confirmed our strong suspicion that this was a pair of Fish Crows. They immediately set upon hanging from the walls-ceiling and tearing apart the nests with their bills. The hubbub of House Sparrows left no doubt that they were seeking  young from several of these old swallow nests. In fact, one flew off with a young House Sparrow in its bill. The other poked into another nest and, finding nothing, flew off after its mate.  The American ornithologist Charles Bendire is cited in Life Histories of North American Jays, Crows and Titmice (A. Continuing FAMILY ROUTINE  of "Adam" the chick and it's two parents. The chick was fed some 6 times on branches through regurgitation and in gape feeding. One of the first feedings was a non-regurgitated large whitish piece of "food" (Fish?) at least 7 cm long by 4 cm wide!! "Adam" took it no problem!!     The family went scouring toward ONEAWAY Ave. and CUMBERLAND Ave. at least 4 times. Usually  adult female stays close to chick "Adam", whereas adult male FICR strays further afield to Lake and east.    Earlier in the am they were quite vocal; even "Adam" was calling. For the fourth straight day no signs of the second fledged chick "Eve" !???. It has gone missing since last Saturday Morning.

Did spot one carrying food (a chicken bone), but he did not look like he intended to share.  ;)  Most of these were fledglings I believe. One was jumping at a herring gull, which was wondering what they hey is going on with this bird, and many were picking up bits of bark and bottle caps, checking everything out. So crow.

Family group of parents and first born “ Adam” interacting. Today there was more “ life skills” teaching from parents to offspring. They broke branches and carried them from tree to tree, interacted vocally, and  fed each other and the chick. Chick seemed to have passed all the “tests”.   They all vocalized some, including the chick, and were territorial y shooing other birds away. Chick fed on regurgitated food on the branches or directly from parental beaks.   All is ‘normal’ Fish Crows Family life. No sign of the second fledgling “Eve”.   Some construction noise nearby, but Fish Crows were not bothered by it. Lots more pictures and videos taken, but foggy gray skies was not suitable for good pics.

The  chick that I have called “Adam” has fledged and flies from tree to tree begging for parental attention! Mostly in the NW region of Adamson Estate where there are two scruffy pines and some tall White Oaks.    Parents regularly come over to attend to “Adam” by regurgitating food into his beak or onto branches and the chick feeds off the branch.   A great deal of interaction between parents and chicks, including branch picking and branch breaking...as if to build another nest or roost..   A fair amount of vocalization by all the family members. Adam the chick , at one point, gave a weirdly shrieking call while diving...it seems that it discovered GRAVITY and that wings must be used to offset GRAVITY!!!.   Parents still very territorial, but did not visit the nest at all. They would just fly by it.   No sign of the second chick “Eve”. Since Friday the 13th ( the last time both chicks were observed being fed at their nest) there has only been one chick observed. Who knows where the other fledged chick has ended up. It definitely is not in or near the nest.     Too many videos and pics taken!!!

Only the two parents observed today, in 2.5 h of careful watching. Quite a mystery as to why the nestling did not show up at all!!!    Parents went to the  nest some 6 times while we were there. They did vocalize some, not much though. They were hanging around by White Oak tree to the lakeside of the nest, and  the usual route—- Spruce Trees to the SE, roofs, eavesthoughs,  NW to Oneways Ave., on Cumberland in the evergreen.   Seem to be picking up detritus low off the groun$.. fairly quiet otherwise. Where are  “Adam and Eve.”..the two offspring??????   Will check again later....today

Media notes: Greenish gloss suggestive of Tamualipas.  This bird did make single croaks, but then later it made repeated awps. We think the audio was consistent with Fish Crow.
Observation Details: 11:30-1:30 pm.  "Mid-day Crow."  This bird made a repertoire of sounds, came and went repeatedly, and appeared to have a narrow beak, which for some time had us thinking we were seeing both a Fish Crow and a Tamaulipas.  It made its typical Fish Crow uh uh.  Later it came back and made single croaks and a repeated series suggestive of a Tamaulipas.   But on close examination of the photos and audio tape, we now think we were just hearing the same Fish Crow in a variety of moods and lights, including the awp awp awp awp.  The frayed tail had a slight wedge shape to it.  The small crow was glossy greenish black. The greenish color seems very consistent with photos of TC on the internet. There was a tiny pinkish area at the base of the mandible.    The location was on the Gulf side of the Highway, in the Treasure Island neighborhood dumpster station.  This experience suggests to be cautious of the single croak calls without an audio recording.  Having the cellphone recording is very helpful in sorting this out, as well as photos showing the tiny pink dot on "both" birds at the base of the mandible.  Further communications from local expert confirmed this as Fish Crow.

Observation Details: This presumed mated pair are occurring regularly here recently. Two relatively small crows, hopping around in the grass along the point in very typical FICR fashion. Minutes before I got home from work Cyrus spotted this bird fly over our yard towards our neighbor's property. After grabbing my camera and binoculars we started trying to relocate it. Shortly after, we heard its nasally "cah" calls coming from the back of our neighbor's property. Earlier Cyrus heard it making their more distinctive "eh-uh" calls. After waiting/searching a little longer we spotted it loosely associating with a group of three American Crows. It was clear the American Crows didn't like the Fish Crow being here, they were constantly chasing/attacking it in flight and scared it off of perches when it landed, but it was still persistently trying to tag along with them. It was very fascinating to watch. When the crows were in flight, the minor structural differences were easier to see. The Fish Crow had an obviously longer tail, more pointed/slender-looking wings, smaller head, and was overall slightly smaller. I got an in-flight photo that shows the comparison fairly well.

Why does the Trowbridge gate trash can often have garbage spilled onto the ground?  Note added Saturday evening, May 7:  Most remarkably, after having studied Common Ravens 'up close and personal' at West Rock over the past twenty years (including a dumpster diving raven adult male at the nearby Katz's Restaurant), in now reviewing these photos I began to doubt this identification of two corvids as being Fish Crows. The heavy beak, spatulate tail, and bristle feathers on the beak all now suggest Common Raven.  Yet, prior to my photographing the birds at East Rock, I heard two Fish Crows calling in the immediate vicinity. The photos are of two different corvids raiding the Trowbridge Drive gate trash can. Their size, as apparent to me at the time, was not consistent with raven but was with Fish Crow. While the photos also suggest smaller corvids than ravens, some of the features want to shout out raven! The closed mind can play curious tricks. Time to check out museum specimens of Fish Crow to confirm that my brain settled on the correct identification.

Observation Details: Continuing/known location; same flock as yesterday, but in location slightly E of Family Dollar/warehouse lot. Max FICR count at one time was 16 feeding on the ground with 2-3 AMCR mixed in. Another 50 crow sp were along the tracks in the vicinity, the majority of which were presumably AMCR. Locality: St. Marks NWR (please consider using a more precise location)

Observation Details: **Extraordinarily high. 1x1 tally of birds flying south along the river.   Fairly early in my walk there were 2 large streams of exclusively Fish Crows heading south (141 & 146 separated by ~20 minutes). These birds were mostly coming in groups of 5-15, and at least 75% of these birds early were calling, making for easy IDs. With 4 stragglers my count sat at 291 (already good for a personal high count, besting the Great Hill mid-summer roost in Weymouth).   However, right as I was about to leave, I heard a much larger flock flying overhead, and raced back to get a better vantage to count them. This pulse of 401 passed in a few minutes, and I strained to keep up my 1x1 tally and not resort to estimating or counting by 5s or 10s. There were then more birds streaming for the next half hour, but at a slower rate that allowed for easier counting (and separating out the handful of American Crows that were coming by at this time).   This count of 1177 obliterated the previous Norfolk County high count set just this month (480 on 11/1/23 at Noon Hill), and is a new high count for the South Shore. There is one Barnstable County count of 1200 in February of birds coming in to Falmouth from Marta's Vineyard (https://ebird.org/checklist/S65273943); otherwise this count is the highest count for the state away from the Lawrence Crow Roost. Even there the high count on eBird for Fish Crows is "only" 1500 (not including a 10,000 count that seems to be a mistake), though I'd imagine a great deal of estimating between the species counts is required there. This is also the new high count for the state during the fall (or indeed any month but January/February). This is all a long way of saying this was an incredible showing and I'm glad I started counting 1x1 right away!  Showing my work: First two streams earlier in the walk: 141, 146, 4  2:35pm: 401, 36, 35, 164, 66, 26, 9, 16, 34, 42  3:10pm: 43, 4, 3, 1

6370 N Newtown Rd (Navy Federal Credit Union & Marriott hotel), Norfolk US-VA 36.84341, -76.18592
Observation Details: Observed, counted and photoed Fish Crows and American Crows within 1.5 city block - for 49 minutes before sunrise. These are in addition to groups of Fish Crows and American Crows I just left - at I-64/I-264 interchange - about one half mile (west) from here.  Initially, I was headed to a church at dead end of Adderly St and Lucas Ave - to check for roosting crows. When I exited I-264E though, I detoured and pulled into Navy Federal Credit Union’s (NFCU) lot - first because of the overwhelming sounds of Fish Crows; but then because there were so many crows on the ground! Once I pulled into the NFCU parking lot, the crows' vocalizations escalated. I could hear American Crows too. The sky was dark; but I also became aware of larger quantities of crows in the tree tops. And then I noticed them on on the rooftops. I drove around all 4 sides of the credit union - to determine the extent. The crows were on the ground, treetops and rooftop on all 4 sides. The adjacent Marriott hotel had more crows - again on the ground, in the treetops and on the very large roof. I drove in and around other nearby buildings to quantify the extent. I came up with 3,288:  1,218 crows on 7 rooftops, 1) Navy Federal Credit Union, 2) Marriott, 3) Cross Road Center (counted 168 crows at 6:19 AM when they had already started leaving), 4) 7-11, 5) Chartway Credit Union, 6) DroneUp and 7) 156 Newtown Road. Crows did not use rooftop of Denny’s - perhaps because it’s a singe story - or cooking smoke was venting from roof.  The Marriott roof is quite large and had several hundred crows. Estimating other 5 buildings had 150 crows each.  600+ on utility cables. From the Cross Road Center parking lot, I started counting crows on the utility lines on this west side of Newtown Rd. When I got to 200, I estimated there were at least 600 crows total on the utility lines on Newtown Road.   720 in treetops - Crows occupied at least 16 treetops at NFCU. With 20 crows each that’s at least 180 crows, but some trees had more/50. Estimating 6 trees x 6 other business with 20 crows each.  250 on the ground at Navy Federal Credit Union (all 4 sides), behind, Marriott and behind Cross Roads Center.  500 in the sky. As the sky began to lighten, I became aware of steady stream of crows flying east.  I estimate 3/4 of the 3,288 were Fish Crows and 1/4 were American Crows. This is based on my initial impression when I arrived and recorded vocalizations.  -In hindsight, I realize I did not check east (behind DroneUp, 156 Newtown or 7-11), the Mexican place or Holiday Inn north of DroneUp or north of Greenwich Rood and I-264. - - - 2,200 on Curlew Dr (2024 Feb) https://ebird.org/checklist/S160654354  1,900 at Newtown Rd (2023 Nov 9) https://ebird.org/checklist/S154056403 3,000+ on Newtown Rd (2023 Nov 5): https://ebird.org/checklist/S153798632 2,500 over Berkley Bridge (2023 Jan): https://ebird.org/checklist/S126835401 1,300 on Hicks Ave (2021 Jan 2): https://ebird.org/checklist/S78529530

Minutes before I got home from work Cyrus spotted this bird fly over our yard towards our neighbor's property. After grabbing my camera and binoculars we started trying to relocate it. Shortly after, we heard its nasally "cah" calls coming from the back of our neighbor's property. Earlier Cyrus heard it making their more distinctive "eh-uh" calls. After waiting/searching a little longer we spotted it loosely associating with a group of three American Crows. It was clear the American Crows didn't like the Fish Crow being here, they were constantly chasing/attacking it in flight and scared it off of perches when it landed, but it was still persistently trying to tag along with them. It was very fascinating to watch. When the crows were in flight, the minor structural differences were easier to see. The Fish Crow had an obviously longer tail, more pointed/slender-looking wings, smaller head, and was overall slightly smaller. I got an in-flight photo that shows the comparison fairly well.

Observation Details: Edit: bird was treated by Wild Bird Fund and released back into Shore Road Park on 7/28! Big shout out to WBF and Jimmy Johnson from Narrows Botanical Garden for helping this bird to have a future. Video of the bird’s release, and original notes   https://m.facebook.com/groups/54673582472/posts/10159221325532473   Severely injured or seriously ill bird, carefully and perhaps somewhat foolishly extracted on foot from the shoulder of the Belt Parkway in midday traffic. Brought to Narrows Botanical Garden on 70th street, which works closely with Wild Bird Fund, where it was immediately given private quarters. Had enough energy for a few big flaps, but was overall listless and did not resist being picked up at all. Looked nearly dead in the car, but immediately perched on a log when placed in an enclosure. Hopeful, but not optimistic. Silent, but appreciably small, slender, and long-tailed in the hand. Not in my possession and certainly not in the hand any longer than necessary. Possibly one of the birds that nest across the street in Shore Road Park, but could be a member of the Hoffman Island night roost as well.

Observation Details: Rare. At 6:55am on May 8, 2022 from the Prince Edward Point Bird Observatory parking area I observed a crow flying south above Long Point Road. The bird called several times, emitting a nasal "gah" note, sounding a bit like a cheap party horn. I called out "Fish Crow!" and Phil Mercier (Bander-in-Charge) and Jess Daze (Deputy Bander) emerged from the banding station and were able to see and hear the bird. Mercier recorded the bird's call. After the initial sighting the bird headed east over Lake Ontario towards Timber Island but then swung back and circled the bird observatory/lighthouse area several times. The crow was present for at least 5 minutes and called 15/20 times. Photographed by me. Recorded by Phil Mercier (initially as eBird incompatible AMR file but now uploaded as a MP4 thanks to the technical expertise of Kyle Blaney).

Observation Details: Après une longue attente, une Corneille de rivage s’est manifesté vers 10:00 dans le petit boisé entre l’école et le boulevard. Une deuxième s’est joint à elle et elles se sont dirigées vers le toit de l’école. Vers 10:30, une CORI était perchée au sommet d’un grand pin au bout du boulevard des étudiants. Enregistrement et photos à venir.

Présence connue Le premier oiseau fut découvert le 11 avril dernier, par Benoit Turgeon et Lise Turgeon.  À mon arrivée, j'ai dû attendre une 12aine de minutes après le retour en classe des élèves, avant de pouvoir entendre un 1er individu. Par la suite, j'ai pu localiser les 2 individus qui se répondaient dans le quartier. Je les ai principalement entendues derrière les blocs appartement face au boisé où se trouve leur nid. Un des individus est venu se percher à plusieurs reprises dans les feuillus bordant le stationnement du bloc appartement qui borde la cour de l'école, au nord-est du boisé.  Elles sont venues se percher fréquemment dans le boisé devant la polyvalente, puis elle descendaient en vol, sur l'asphalte, au centre de la rue pour aller ramasser je ne sais trop quoi... possiblement des restes de nourriture ou des insectes. Elles se sont donc promenées entre le boisé et les grands conifères(Pins blancs principalement) de l'autre côté de la rue et derrière les appartements, sans jamais aller à leur nid, situé au sommet du grand plus Pin blanc, durant le temps de ma présence(environ 1h), mais à chaque fois elles venaient se percher dans le boisé de la polyvalente quand même tout près du nid, à moins de 15-20 pieds.  N'ayant pas observé de Corneille d'Amérique durant ma période d'observation, je n'ai pas pu avoir de comparatif direct avec la taille de la Corneille de rivage. Mais comme les 2 Corneilles de rivage sont venues se poser, à plusieurs reprises très près de moi, sur l'asphalte au centre du boulevard, j'ai pu les observer de près, à moins de 12 pieds de moi. Elles m'ont semblé en apparence de taille très petite, et surtout beaucoup moins costaudes qu'une Corneille d'Amérique.   -Le bec m'a semblé très court. -Queue courte droite et carrée.  J'ai donc entendu leur cri très nasillard distinctif et singulier:  -"aw-waah ou ca-caw" occasionnels et répétés. -Cri vraiment très différent du cri de notre Corneille d'Amérique. Il n'y a vraiment aucune confusion possible. J'ai aussi entendu 2 autres cris très différents de leur répertoire qu'elles ont aussi émise. Enregistrements et photos à venir.  Lifer #359(Qc)

Photo, video, poor audio due to wind, awk, awk-awk call many times. Harassing gulls for food! Small glossy black crow harassing Ring-billed Gulls for food. Video of it chasing after the Gulls. The bird was rather ragged looking compared to an American Crow but the strong wind could have caused that. Quite rounded tail when sitting and appeared fairly straight across in flight. Closed the wings were more oval at the neck than American Crow. The crown of the head was more flat and beak was more gradually tapered than American Crow. Its call was mostly a two note raspy Awk-Awk and periodically Awk-----Awk-Awk. The throat feathers protruded out like a small beard when it called.

This shows the small size and stocky appearance of the Fish Crow while perched.  It had a steeper forehead and less of a neck compared to the American Crow perched above.
Observation Details: Photos,  audio.  See general checklist comments above for more details and background.  Over six hours I had five encounters with the Fish Crows with a total of about 20-25 minutes of observation.  They were very vocal during the encounters, both on the ground and in flight which made it easy to locate them.  They were seen near American Crows at times but never associating with them and if an American got too close they would aggressively drive it away.   Observations and comparisons were the following.  The Fish Crows had a short and chunky/squatty appearance when perched and while walking on the ground, compared to large, sleek, stretched-out look of the Americans Crows.  The Fish Crows gave single note “uh” calls and double-note “uh-uh” calls, where the duration was short and abrupt.  American Crow juveniles when begging make longer single note calls and never do a double-note.  Also, none of the American Crows were making begging calls.  Whereas the American Crows had a scaly appearance to the feathers on their upper backs, the Fish Crows appeared to have a smooth appearance.  When I could do a direct size comparison (Fish Crow chasing American right behind it) there was an obvious size difference with the Fish Crow appearing much smaller.  The Fish Crow wing shape was more pointed with P9 similar in size or slightly longer than P5.  The American Crows were more blunt-ended in shape with P9 appearing shorter than P5.  The Fish Crows at times appeared to have no necks since they would fluff up their throat feathers whereas the Americans would stretch their necks out, especially when calling.  When the Fish Crows called, they assumed a more hunched over posture whereas the Americans were more upright and stretched out their necks at a higher angle.  The Fish Crows did not associate closely with the American Crow flock but would sometimes be near the flock.  Audio clips and more photos in this checklist:  https://ebird.org/view/checklist/S47953561

**Extraordinarily high. 1x1 tally of birds flying south along the river.   Fairly early in my walk there were 2 large streams of exclusively Fish Crows heading south (141 & 146 separated by ~20 minutes). These birds were mostly coming in groups of 5-15, and at least 75% of these birds early were calling, making for easy IDs. With 4 stragglers my count sat at 291 (already good for a personal high count, besting the Great Hill mid-summer roost in Weymouth).   However, right as I was about to leave, I heard a much larger flock flying overhead, and raced back to get a better vantage to count them. This pulse of 401 passed in a few minutes, and I strained to keep up my 1x1 tally and not resort to estimating or counting by 5s or 10s. There were then more birds streaming for the next half hour, but at a slower rate that allowed for easier counting (and separating out the handful of American Crows that were coming by at this time).   This count of 1177 obliterated the previous Norfolk County high count set just this month (480 on 11/1/23 at Noon Hill), and is a new high count for the South Shore. There is one Barnstable County count of 1200 in February of birds coming in to Falmouth from Marta's Vineyard (https://ebird.org/checklist/S65273943); otherwise this count is the highest count for the state away from the Lawrence Crow Roost. Even there the high count on eBird for Fish Crows is "only" 1500 (not including a 10,000 count that seems to be a mistake), though I'd imagine a great deal of estimating between the species counts is required there. This is also the new high count for the state during the fall (or indeed any month but January/February). This is all a long way of saying this was an incredible showing and I'm glad I started counting 1x1 right away!  Showing my work: First two streams earlier in the walk: 141, 146, 4  2:35pm: 401, 36, 35, 164, 66, 26, 9, 16, 34, 42  3:10pm: 43, 4, 3, 1

Observation Details: Apparently mated male/female pair and third individual that stays close and is tolerated for the most part, but often chased away by what appears to be the female. Their “Birds of the World” account states this is apparently a frequent occurrence during the nesting stage. All three vocalized together for great identification opportunity. Male often goes to rest on the ledge of the large window over the Giant Eagle entrance, calling while facing the window in what seems like an attempt to amplify his voice over all of the background noise. Lots of single note, high-pitched and nasal “caw” calls with quite a bit of triple “caw-caw-caw” calls mixed in but not very many double “UH-uh” calls heard. Observed carrying sticks twice. Once they flew to the south with a stick towards the neighborhood around Henderson Road, the other time the female appeared to go east along Bethel with a stick and then return without it. Attempted to locate nest and found four good candidates but not sure if they are current or old as no birds were seen actively visiting them.
A real one. Not the red-winged blackbirds that always try to fool us.

Family group of parents and first born “ Adam” interacting. Today there was more “ life skills” teaching from parents to offspring. They broke branches and carried them from tree to tree, interacted vocally, and  fed each other and the chick. Chick seemed to have passed all the “tests”.   They all vocalized some, including the chick, and were territorial y shooing other birds away. Chick fed on regurgitated food on the branches or directly from parental beaks.   All is ‘normal’ Fish Crows Family life. No sign of the second fledgling “Eve”.   Some construction noise nearby, but Fish Crows were not bothered by it. Lots more pictures and videos taken, but foggy gray skies was not suitable for good pics.

At least 4 birds.  Heard briefly vocalizing.  Photos.  The vocalizations heard were the "uh-uh" two note call as opposed to the "Caw" calls heard by American Crows.  While I cannot say that I have vast experience with Fish Crows, as fortune would have it I took a trip to FL earlier in the year and was able to hear many Fish Crows calling, and even fed some french fries at a Dairy Queen near Ding Darling preserve.  This experience definitely enhanced my ability to hear the diagnostic "uh-uh" of the birds at Chapel Hill.  I was also able to get many photos, but recording was not possible that day due to high winds.  I did subsequently record Fish Crows from this same area later, as can be found in eBird reports.  I hope that this is helpful for this record.

This crow originally spotted by Linda Barry-Cooper on 7 Oct and believed to be a Fish Crow.  This day, 9 Oct is the 2nd sighting with Duncan Millis in location of Nandana Resort in gravel parking lot , the bird appeared lame, sick or injured. Duncan and I captured and placed in back of his SUV and was transported to Linda Bird residence and provided fresh water and food. Overall the crow Very weak and lethargic. May have been in fight or is sick or ate something poison.  Confirmation on Species came from Bruce Purdy & Bruce Hallett after several measurements sent in for verification. The crow passed away on 10/10 in the evening.  The bird is now in a freezer and is being transported on ice to Elsworth Weir BNT on 10/14/2015 for further transport to Univ of Florida.  Measurements are as follows: Length=13 inches/34mm from tip of bill to tip of tail.  Culmen and or head= 3" or 7.5mm from back of skull to tip of beak.  Wing is 11" from bend of wing on ruler to tip of longest primary.  Wingspan is 21 inches however not sure if I am spreading wings out correctly or enough.  TAIL is 6 inches. Foot is 4mm  excluding claw.  Bill is 4mm.  TWO MORE MEASUREMENTS WERE TAKEN BY REQUEST OF BRUCE HALLETT ON 10/12.  Tarsus Length= 1 3/4 inches or 3.5 cm. Vernier Caliper reading is 38mm.  BILL from nostril opening anterior side to end of bill= 1.2 or 1.3 " inches respectively.  FINAL SYNOPSIS FROM BRUCE HALLET READS: The popular North American field guides list the Fish Crow as smaller in size, smaller billed and with shorter legs along with its call as being distinguishable traits when compared to American Crow.  You did some measurements  with a flexible ruler as best you could on your crow which was now a refrigerated specimen.  Lying the bird on its back, you took a measurement from the tip of its bill to the tip of the tail for length.  It showed 13 " but was probably a little longer because the head and bill were not stretched out.  Fish Crows are listed as around 15" long whereas Am Crows are listed as around 17.5" which gives a nod to Fish Crow. Next, at my request, you measured the distance on the bill between the nostrils or nares and the tip, a hard measurement to take without the proper equipment.  Your take was between 1.2 and 1.3 inches which translates to around 30/34 millimeters and according to Peter Pyle's book Identification Guide to North American Birds Part I (1997) falls within the Fish Crow parameters of 25.7-34.2 mm.  American Crow is 28-44.0 mm and that includes all the  smaller subspecies. Lastly,  you took a tarsus measurement based on Pyle's requirements, and you came up with 1.75" which translates to 44.45 mm.  Pyle reads Fish Crow parameters as 41.5-49.6 mm and American Crow as 53.0-66.5 mm.  Tarsus measurement to Fish Crow. We did not perform this process Linda according to exact scientific specifications.  However, you took enough calculations, however crude, to determine that you had a smaller, shorter billed and shorter legged crow which suggests a Fish Crow.  So I think you can now back up yours and Duncan's observation with confidence and I believe you already have. Thanks for your timeliness and focused efforts.  Bruce Hallett

Photos linked below were all taken at this site during this visit.    The bird was very tame, allowing close approach and feeding on the expected urban detritus, including a road-killed small bird, a discarded roll, and various other quasi-food items. Several items were taken to a puddle where they were immersed in water before being eaten.    The bird vocalized a lot initially, always giving single syllabled "ahh" calls with a nasal quality. We left ten minutes later when the bird flew south and we pursued it.                        Andy posted a description to the ID-Frontiers listserv, and responses so far have all supported this identification, including those from Brian Sullivan, David Sibley, Kevin McGowan, and Michael OBrien.

Unlike yesterday, there was hardly any vocalizing today. Both parents were scavenging east of the nest, past the Pet cemetery, at the beginning. They made some trips to the nest to feed the chicks.     One of the chicks, we call Adam,  is almost ready to fly away from the nest. It climbed up on the branches and moved to nearby branches about 1 m away and back to the nest. All of the primaries are almost fully grown. It is ready to move away from the nest. Parents fed it about 1 m away from the nest site.     The other is less active, perhaps named EVE,  and stays in the nest  without coming out. Not as far along in the moult.      Both parents made at least 6 trips to scavenging areas,...roofs..eaves throughs , evergreen trees and back to nest area.     No Hawks and No Ravens ( although someone told us that yesterday evening there was a RAVEN around that caused  an angry territorial response by the Fish Crows..shooing the Raven out of the area..quite a commotion apparently.   Many pictures and videos taken.

This crow originally spotted by Linda Barry-Cooper on 7 Oct and believed to be a Fish Crow.  This day, 9 Oct is the 2nd sighting with Duncan Millis in location of Nandana Resort in gravel parking lot , the bird appeared lame, sick or injured. Duncan and I captured and placed in back of his SUV and was transported to Linda Bird residence and provided fresh water and food. Overall the crow Very weak and lethargic. May have been in fight or is sick or ate something poison.  Confirmation on Species came from Bruce Purdy & Bruce Hallett after several measurements sent in for verification. The crow passed away on 10/10 in the evening.  The bird is now in a freezer and is being transported on ice to Elsworth Weir BNT on 10/14/2015 for further transport to Univ of Florida.  Measurements are as follows: Length=13 inches/34mm from tip of bill to tip of tail.  Culmen and or head= 3" or 7.5mm from back of skull to tip of beak.  Wing is 11" from bend of wing on ruler to tip of longest primary.  Wingspan is 21 inches however not sure if I am spreading wings out correctly or enough.  TAIL is 6 inches. Foot is 4mm  excluding claw.  Bill is 4mm.  TWO MORE MEASUREMENTS WERE TAKEN BY REQUEST OF BRUCE HALLETT ON 10/12.  Tarsus Length= 1 3/4 inches or 3.5 cm. Vernier Caliper reading is 38mm.  BILL from nostril opening anterior side to end of bill= 1.2 or 1.3 " inches respectively.  FINAL SYNOPSIS FROM BRUCE HALLET READS: The popular North American field guides list the Fish Crow as smaller in size, smaller billed and with shorter legs along with its call as being distinguishable traits when compared to American Crow.  You did some measurements  with a flexible ruler as best you could on your crow which was now a refrigerated specimen.  Lying the bird on its back, you took a measurement from the tip of its bill to the tip of the tail for length.  It showed 13 " but was probably a little longer because the head and bill were not stretched out.  Fish Crows are listed as around 15" long whereas Am Crows are listed as around 17.5" which gives a nod to Fish Crow. Next, at my request, you measured the distance on the bill between the nostrils or nares and the tip, a hard measurement to take without the proper equipment.  Your take was between 1.2 and 1.3 inches which translates to around 30/34 millimeters and according to Peter Pyle's book Identification Guide to North American Birds Part I (1997) falls within the Fish Crow parameters of 25.7-34.2 mm.  American Crow is 28-44.0 mm and that includes all the  smaller subspecies. Lastly,  you took a tarsus measurement based on Pyle's requirements, and you came up with 1.75" which translates to 44.45 mm.  Pyle reads Fish Crow parameters as 41.5-49.6 mm and American Crow as 53.0-66.5 mm.  Tarsus measurement to Fish Crow. We did not perform this process Linda according to exact scientific specifications.  However, you took enough calculations, however crude, to determine that you had a smaller, shorter billed and shorter legged crow which suggests a Fish Crow.  So I think you can now back up yours and Duncan's observation with confidence and I believe you already have. Thanks for your timeliness and focused efforts.  Bruce Hallett

Media notes: Smaller fish crow on the right compared to larger American crow on the left.
Observation Details: Initially, resting with gulls on parking lot surface.  Soon, they all took off to the Hannaford parking lot where someone had dumped out, what looked like, a pile of whole-kernel corn.  Even though dozens of gulls were crowded around the site, the fish crow was able to grab some bites before the corn was all gobbled up by the gulls.  After the corn was gone, apparently some bits remained which the fish crow and and an American crow were feasting on.  The smaller size of the fish crow was quite noticeable compared to the larger American crow a few inches away.  Photos obtained.  The 1st photo is a close-up of the fish crow from only about 2 meters.  The 2nd photo is a size comparison showing the two crow species cleaning up the corn bits - the smaller fish crow on is on the left and the larger American crow is on the right.  In the 3rd photo the two crow species have switched places, with the smaller fish crow on the right and the larger American crow on the left.
